results.description: A Malware Callback alert detects network activity that matches a malware command and control (C2) signature. This should only fire when a host is already compromised. The recommended action is to investigate the host and possibly remove it from the network. This activity will be blocked if the NX is in block mode.
This rule alerts on Malware-Callback events generated by FireEye NX appliances.

A Malware Callback alert detects network activity that matches a malware command and control (C2) signature. This should only fire when a host is already compromised. The recommended action is to investigate the host and possibly remove it from the network. This activity will be blocked if the NX is in block mode.
This rule alerts on Domain-Match events generated by FireEye NX appliances.

A Domain Match event detects when a client has requested DNS to resolve a known malicious hostname. This alert just means that DNS was resolved. It does not indicate that any malicious payload was downloaded. Since this alert does not confirm a compromise, it will take additional work to determine the level of response needed. Several hits from the same source to unique hostnames may be a better indicator of a compromised machine. This activity will not be blocked if the NX is in block mode.
This rule alerts on Domain-Match events generated by FireEye NX appliances.

A Domain Match event detects when a client has requested DNS to resolve a known malicious hostname. This alert just means that DNS was resolved. It does not indicate that any malicious payload was downloaded. Since this alert does not confirm a compromise, it will take additional work to determine the level of response needed. Several hits from the same source to unique hostnames may be a better indicator of a compromised machine. This activity will not be blocked if the NX is in block mode.
This rule alerts on Infection-Match events generated by FireEye NX appliances.

An Infection Match event detects when a host accesses a URL that is known to be malicious. These alerts mean that a URL was accessed, but does not confirm that malicious payload was actually downloaded. If malicious payload was downloaded, it still may not mean the host is compromised. For example, the malicious may contain an exploit the host is patched for. These events will be blocked if the NX is in block mode.
